Lab Architecture

Overview
This lab builds a network monitoring system that mirrors how enterprise infrastructure monitoring is designed with a dedicated monitoring zone, segmented networks, and zone-path awareness rather than just device-level monitoring.

The core design principle: monitor paths and zones, not just devices.

Physical layout

Everything runs as virtual machines on a single Windows host running VMware Workstation. The VMs are connected through VMware virtual networks (VMnets) that simulate real physical network segments.

Virtual machines

pfSense VM -> role: Firewall, gateway, and zone boundary enforcement

Network adapters:
Adapter 1: VMnet0 (Bridged) → WAN interface (em0) — gets IP from home router
Adapter 2: VMnet1 (Host-only) → LAN interface (em1) — 192.168.X.X
Adapter 3: VMnet2 (Host-only) → DMZ interface (em2) — 172.16.X.X

Why pfSense sits here: pfSense is the routing and security boundary between all three zones. Every packet crossing zones passes through pfSense and is evaluated against its firewall rules. 
This gives centralised traffic control and the ability to monitor inter-zone connectivity by checking whether pfSense can route between zones correctly.

Ubuntu DMZ Server (Zabbix server) -> role: Monitoring server — data collection, storage, alerting, web UI

Network adapters:

Adapter 1: VMnet2 (host-only) — 172.16.X.X/24, gateway 172.16.X.X and Adapter 2: VMnet8 (NAT for Management) — 192.168.X.X/24 (no gateway)

The monitoring server needs to reach every zone to collect data. From DMZ it can initiate connections to LAN hosts (agent polling), to pfSense (SNMP queries), and to WAN (internet health checks). It can also receive inbound connections from the Raspberry Pi via pfSense port forward.
The second adapter on VMnet8 provides a direct management path from the host machine that bypasses pfSense entirely. This is essential during lab configuration — when pfSense rules are being adjusted and might break connectivity, SSH access via VMnet8 still works.

Software stack:

Zabbix Server 7.0
MariaDB 10.x (metrics database)
Apache 2.4 (web frontend)
Zabbix Agent (self-monitoring)

Linux VM -> role: Internal LAN host represents typical enterprise workstation

Network adapters:

Adapter 1: VMnet1 (LAN) — 192.168.X.X/24, gateway 192.168.X.X

Monitoring: Zabbix Agent 2 installed, reporting to 172.16.X.X

It represents a real internal host that Zabbix monitors via agent. Demonstrates LAN-to-DMZ agent communication through pfSense firewall rules. Also serves as the test point for LAN-zone monitoring.

Raspberry Pi -> role: External node on home LAN represents a device outside pfSense. It's connected to home router LAN — 192.168.X.X

Monitoring: ICMP only (Zabbix agent not available for ARM64 on Ubuntu 24.04)

The Pi sits outside pfSense on the home network, which means monitoring it requires traffic to traverse pfSense WAN. This tests whether pfSense is correctly port forwarding inbound connections and makes the external LAN zone visible in the monitoring system.
